The Chronicle Ricky Zililo, Senior Sports Reporter
WARRIORS captain Knowledge Musona has been named among the 15 best Kaizer Chiefs FC foreign signings by South African leading football magazine Soccer Laduma. <img class="wp-image-541315 size-full" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2021/04/nkatha.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2021/04/nkatha.jpg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2021/04/nkatha-360x200.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> Zimbabwean Kingston Nkhatha had an on and off relationship with Chiefs fans but played a key role in Amakhosi’s league title success under Stuart Baxter. Pic: Soccer Laduma Musona, now plying his trade in Belgium, is among seven Zimbabweans that the publication rated as part of Chiefs’ best foreign signings, with former Zambian striker Collins Mbesuma leading the perk. <img class="wp-image-541304 size-full" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2021/04/bhasera.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2021/04/bhasera.jpg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2021/04/bhasera-360x200.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> Onismor Bhasera was not at Chiefs for long, but made an impact before leaving for England. Pic: Soccer Laduma The publication rated Musona as the third best Chiefs import, with Onismor Bhasera (now at Supersport United) in sixth place followed by ex-Highlanders and Dynamos central defender Thomas Sweswe, striker Kingston Nkatha, roving wingback Robson Muchichwa and Willard Katsande. <img class="wp-image-541305 size-full" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2021/04/svesve.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2021/04/svesve.jpg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2021/04/svesve-360x200.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> Zimbabwean defender Thomas Sweswe was there for Amakhosi’s Telkom Knockout successes in 2009 and 2010. Pic: Soccer Laduma Ex-midfielder Tinashe Nengomasha came in at number 14. <img class="wp-image-541308 size-full" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2021/04/nengo.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2021/04/nengo.jpg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2021/04/nengo-360x200.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> Zimbabwean Tinashe Nengomasha is a Chiefs legend. Pic: Soccer Laduma The lists also has Ghanaian defender Jonathan Quartey at number two, Nigeria’s Muisi Ajao (4), Malawi legend Patrick Mabedi (5), the Namibian pair of Robert Nauseb and Mohammed Ouseb at number 11 and 12 as well as Burundi’s Valery Nahao (13). <img class="wp-image-541311 size-full" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2021/04/katsande.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2021/04/katsande.jpg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2021/04/katsande-360x200.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> Zimbabwean midfielder Willard Katsande has been with Chiefs for 10 years. Pic: Soccer Laduma Former Uganda international David Obua completes the list. <img class="wp-image-541312 size-full" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2021/04/robson.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2021/04/robson.jpg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2021/04/robson-360x200.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> Zimbabwe’s Robson Muchichwa made his mark with the Soweto giants. Pic: Soccer Laduma Presently, Chiefs are home to the Zimbabwean pair of Katsande, who has served the club for a decade and striker Khama Billiat. – @ZililoR